Yes, a class can implement multiple interfaces in Java. Unlike class inheritance (single inheritance), interfaces support multiple inheritance of type. This is one of the key design advantages of interfaces.

## Why Multiple Interface Implementation?

Java interfaces define contracts (method signatures) without implementation details. A class can fulfill multiple contracts simultaneously, allowing for composition of behaviors.

### Code Example:
```java
interface Animal {
    void eat();
    void sleep();
}

interface Flyer {
    void fly();
    int getMaxAltitude();
}

interface Swimmer {
    void swim();
}

public class Duck implements Animal, Flyer, Swimmer {
    @Override
    public void eat() {
        System.out.println("Duck eats seeds and insects");
    }

    @Override
    public void sleep() {
        System.out.println("Duck sleeps with one eye open");
    }

    @Override
    public void fly() {
        System.out.println("Duck flies at moderate speed");
    }

    @Override
    public int getMaxAltitude() {
        return 4000; // feet
    }

    @Override
    public void swim() {
        System.out.println("Duck swims with webbed feet");
    }
}
```

## Why Encapsulation is Critical:

1. **Flexibility**: A class can represent multiple roles/behaviors
2. **No Diamond Problem**: Java 8+ handles default methods gracefully
3. **Loose Coupling**: Code depends on abstractions, not concrete classes
4. **Real-World Modeling**: Objects often play multiple roles

Key Benefits: Plugin architectures, decorator patterns, service composition in microservices.

Method overloading and overriding are two distinct concepts in Java polymorphism, operating at different times.

## Method Overloading (Compile-Time Polymorphism)

Occurs when multiple methods have the same name but **different parameter signatures** in the same class.

```java
public class Calculator {
    public int add(int a, int b) {
        return a + b;
    }

    public int add(int a, int b, int c) {
        return a + b + c;
    }

    public double add(double a, double b) {
        return a + b;
    }

    public String concatenate(String s, int i) {
        return s + i;
    }

    public String concatenate(int i, String s) {
        return i + s;
    }
}
```

## Method Overriding (Runtime Polymorphism)

Occurs when a **subclass provides a specific implementation** of a method already defined in the parent class/interface.

```java
class Animal {
    public void makeSound() {
        System.out.println("Generic animal sound");
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    @Override
    public void makeSound() {
        System.out.println("Woof! Woof!");
    }
}
```

## Comparison:

Overloading: Same class, different parameters, compile-time binding
Overriding: Parent-child classes, same signature, runtime binding

Production Impact: Autoboxing complicates overloading; method shadowing can cause confusion.

Encapsulation is an OOP principle that bundles data (variables) and methods together while hiding internal implementation details from the outside world through access modifiers.

## Key Concept: Data Hiding

```java
public class BankAccount {
    private double balance = 0;
    private String accountNumber;

    public void deposit(double amount) {
        if (amount <= 0) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Amount must be positive");
        }
        balance += amount;
    }

    public boolean withdraw(double amount) {
        if (amount > balance || amount <= 0) {
            return false;
        }
        balance -= amount;
        return true;
    }

    public double getBalance() {
        return balance;
    }
}
```

## Why Important:

1. **Data Integrity**: Prevents external code from corrupting data
2. **Validation**: Ensures all modifications meet business rules
3. **Flexibility**: Change internal implementation without affecting clients
4. **Security**: Sensitive data remains hidden

## Real-World Impact:

Thread-safe getters/setters, transaction management, database abstraction layers all depend on proper encapsulation.

Encapsulation is the foundation of maintainable, secure, and scalable Java applications.

Polymorphism means "many forms" - the ability of objects/methods to take multiple forms. Java supports compile-time and runtime polymorphism.

## Compile-Time Polymorphism (Method Overloading)

Resolved by the compiler at **compile time**.

```java
public class PaymentProcessor {
    public void process(CreditCard card) {
        System.out.println("Processing credit card");
    }

    public void process(PayPalAccount account) {
        System.out.println("Processing PayPal");
    }

    public void process(Bitcoin wallet) {
        System.out.println("Processing Bitcoin");
    }
}

PaymentProcessor processor = new PaymentProcessor();
processor.process(new CreditCard());    // Compiler knows exact version
processor.process(new PayPalAccount()); // Determined at compile-time
```

## Runtime Polymorphism (Method Overriding)

Resolved by the **JVM at runtime**.

```java
abstract class PaymentMethod {
    public abstract void processPayment(double amount);
}

class CreditCard extends PaymentMethod {
    @Override
    public void processPayment(double amount) {
        System.out.println("Processing via Credit Card");
    }
}

PaymentMethod payment = selectPaymentMethod();  // Runtime decision
payment.processPayment(100);  // JVM calls correct version at runtime
```

## Key Differences:

Compile-time (Overloading): Based on parameter types, Static binding, Faster
Runtime (Overriding): Based on object type, Dynamic binding, Minor overhead

Polymorphism enables extensible systems and plugin architectures.

OutOfMemoryError occurs when the JVM cannot allocate sufficient heap memory for new objects.

## Main Causes:

### 1. Memory Leak (Most Common)
Objects no longer used but remain referenced, preventing GC.

```java
public class MemoryLeakExample {
    static List<byte[]> memoryLeak = new ArrayList<>();

    public void leakyMethod() {
        while (true) {
            byte[] memory = new byte[1024 * 1024];
            memoryLeak.add(memory);  // NEVER REMOVED
            // GC cannot collect - memory accumulates
        }
    }
}
```

### 2. Unbounded Collections
Collections grow without removal.

```java
static Map<String, byte[]> cache = new HashMap<>();
// No eviction policy - grows indefinitely
```

### 3. ThreadLocal Misuse
```java
static ThreadLocal<byte[]> buffer = ThreadLocal.withInitial(...);
// In servlet with thread pool - data stays after request
// FIX: Always remove in finally block
```

### 4. Unintended Static References
Static members retain objects for application lifetime.

### 5. External Resource Exhaustion
Connection leaks, file handles never closed.

```java
try (Connection conn = DriverManager.getConnection(url)) {
    // Use connection
}  // Auto-closed
```

## Prevention:

1. Use bounded caches with eviction policy
2. Monitor memory with JVM flags
3. Proper resource management (try-with-resources)
4. Regular memory profiling

OutOfMemoryError is preventable with proper memory management.

The Java Memory Model (JMM) is a formal specification that defines how threads interact through memory. It guarantees visibility and ordering of memory operations across multiple threads.

## Core Concepts:

### Visibility
Changes made by one thread are visible to other threads.

```java
public class VisibilityExample {
    private boolean flag = false;

    public void writer() {
        flag = true;  // Write
    }

    public void reader() {
        if (flag) {   // Read - when is this true?
            // ...
        }
    }
}

// Without synchronization: reader might not see flag=true
// With synchronization or volatile: visibility guaranteed
```

### Ordering
Memory operations may not execute in program order without synchronization.

```java
int x = 0, y = 0;
x = 1;      // Memory write
y = x + 1;  // Read x, write y

// On single-core: always y=2
// On multi-core without sync: CPU may reorder
// y might = 1 (x not written yet from CPU perspective)
```

## Happens-Before Relationships

Operations ordered by these relationships are guaranteed to be visible:

1. **Program order**: Within a thread, statements execute in order
2. **Synchronization**: unlock happens-before subsequent lock
3. **Volatile**: Write to volatile happens-before read
4. **Thread start**: start() happens-before first action of thread
5. **Thread termination**: final action happens-before join() returns

```java
public class JMMExample {
    private volatile boolean ready = false;
    private int value = 0;

    public void writer() {
        value = 42;      // Write
        ready = true;    // Volatile write
    }

    public void reader() {
        if (ready) {     // Volatile read
            System.out.println(value);  // GUARANTEED to print 42
        }
    }
}
```

## Real Production Impact:

```java
// WRONG - No ordering guarantee
private int counter = 0;
public void increment() {
    counter++;  // Not thread-safe
}

// CORRECT - Synchronization creates happens-before
public synchronized void increment() {
    counter++;
}

// CORRECT - Volatile for simple cases
private volatile boolean shutdown = false;
public void stop() {
    shutdown = true;
}
```

JMM is the contract between compiler, runtime, and hardware ensuring correctness.

Java provides four levels of object references with different behaviors regarding garbage collection.

## Strong References (Normal References)

```java
List<String> list = new ArrayList<>();  // STRONG reference
String str = "hello";                   // STRONG reference

// Object is NOT collected while strong references exist
list.add("data");
list = null;  // Now eligible for GC (no more strong refs)
```

## Weak References

Used when you want the object to be GC'd even if referenced.

```java
import java.lang.ref.WeakReference;

public class WeakRefExample {
    static WeakReference<String> weakRef =
        new WeakReference<>(new String("temporary"));

    public void checkRef() {
        String value = weakRef.get();
        if (value != null) {
            System.out.println(value);
        } else {
            System.out.println("Object was garbage collected");
        }
    }
}

// Use case: Caches that should be cleared under memory pressure
```

## Soft References

Like weak references but kept longer - only collected when memory needed.

```java
import java.lang.ref.SoftReference;

public class ImageCache {
    private Map<String, SoftReference<BufferedImage>> cache
        = new HashMap<>();

    public void cacheImage(String key, BufferedImage img) {
        cache.put(key, new SoftReference<>(img));
    }

    public BufferedImage getImage(String key) {
        SoftReference<BufferedImage> ref = cache.get(key);
        return ref != null ? ref.get() : null;
    }
}

// Use case: Memory-efficient caches (images, documents)
// Cleared only when heap pressure increases
```

## Phantom References

Most esoteric - useful only with ReferenceQueue for cleanup operations.

```java
import java.lang.ref.PhantomReference;
import java.lang.ref.ReferenceQueue;

public class ResourceCleanup {
    private ReferenceQueue<MyResource> queue = new ReferenceQueue<>();

    public void trackResource(MyResource res) {
        new PhantomReference<>(res, queue);
    }

    public void runCleanup() {
        MyPhantomRef ref;
        while ((ref = (MyPhantomRef) queue.poll()) != null) {
            ref.cleanup();  // Cleanup triggered after object GC'd
        }
    }
}

// Use case: Guaranteed cleanup operations (close resources)
```

## Comparison Table:

```
Strong: Normal objects, GC'd when unreferenced
Weak: GC'd immediately if only weak refs exist
Soft: GC'd only under memory pressure
Phantom: GC'd, use for cleanup notifications
```

Real-world use: Cache frameworks (Guava, Spring Cache) use these extensively.

HashMap is a hash table-based implementation using arrays and linked lists (or trees in Java 8+).

## Structure

```java
// Internal structure
private Node<K,V>[] table;

// Each Node is a key-value pair with hash
static class Node<K,V> implements Map.Entry<K,V> {
    final int hash;
    final K key;
    V value;
    Node<K,V> next;  // Linked list for collisions
}
```

## Put Operation: Step-by-Step

```java
HashMap<String, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();
map.put("alice", 25);

// Steps:
// 1. Compute hash: hash("alice") = -1234567 (example)
// 2. Get index: index = (-1234567) & (16-1) = 9
// 3. Check table[9]:
//    - If empty: insert new Node
//    - If occupied: check for collision
//       - Same key? Update value
//       - Different key? Add to linked list (or tree)
```

## Get Operation

```java
map.get("alice");

// Steps:
// 1. Compute hash: hash("alice") = -1234567
// 2. Get index: index = 9
// 3. Walk linked list at table[9]:
//    - If key found: return value
//    - If not found: return null
```

## Rehashing/Resizing

When load factor (elements/capacity) exceeds threshold (default 0.75):

```java
// Original capacity: 16
// 12 elements added (0.75 * 16 = 12)
// Trigger: Rehash to capacity 32

// All existing elements rehashed to new positions
// index = hash & (newCapacity - 1)  // Different index!
```

## Java 8 Optimization: Tree Buckets

When bucket has >8 nodes, convert to red-black tree:

```java
// Before Java 8:
table[5] = node1 -> node2 -> node3 -> ... (linked list)
// O(n) lookup worst case

// Java 8+:
table[5] = Red-Black Tree of nodes
// O(log n) lookup
```

## Hash Collision Example

```java
class Key {
    String value;

    @Override
    public int hashCode() {
        return value.hashCode();
    }

    @Override
    public boolean equals(Object o) {
        return ((Key)o).value.equals(this.value);
    }
}

// If two keys hash to same index:
map.put(new Key("a"), 1);   // table[5]
map.put(new Key("b"), 2);   // Also table[5]

// Collision handling:
// table[5] -> Key("a"):1 -> Key("b"):2
```

Performance: O(1) average, O(n) worst case (all same hash).

Hash collisions occur when two different keys hash to the same index. HashMap handles them gracefully.

## Collision Handling: Chaining

```java
HashMap<String, String> map = new HashMap<>();
map.put("John", "25");
map.put("Jane", "23");

// Assume both hash to index 5:
// table[5] -> John:25 -> Jane:23

// This is a linked list of collisions
```

## Java 8+ Optimization

When a bucket reaches TREEIFY_THRESHOLD (8 nodes):

```java
// Before: Linked list
table[5] -> node1 -> node2 -> ... -> node8 (8 nodes, O(n) lookup)

// After: Red-Black Tree
table[5] -> TreeNode (balanced binary search, O(log n) lookup)
```

## Impact on Performance

```java
// Good hash function: Even distribution
// Few collisions -> O(1) lookup

// Poor hash function: Many collisions
// Many collisions -> O(n) lookup worst case

class BadHash {
    @Override
    public int hashCode() {
        return 1;  // All keys hash to 1 - terrible!
    }
}

map.put(new BadHash(), "value1");
map.put(new BadHash(), "value2");
// table[1] -> node1 -> node2 (linked list, O(n) lookup)
```

## Resize/Rehash

When capacity exceeded, rehash moves elements to new indices:

```java
// Original: capacity=16
put(0, "a");  put(1, "b");  ...  put(12, "m");  // 12/16 = 0.75
// Threshold (0.75*16=12) reached

// Rehash: capacity=32
// All elements get new index: index = hash & (32-1)

// Reduces collisions:
// Before: 3 elements at index 5
// After: scattered across new indices
```

## Real-World Impact

```java
// HashMap with poor hash codes
Set<BadObject> set = new HashSet<>();
for (int i = 0; i < 100000; i++) {
    set.add(new BadObject(i));  // All hash to same bucket
    // Performance degrades: O(n) instead of O(1)
}
```

## Prevention

```java
public class GoodHash {
    private String id;

    @Override
    public int hashCode() {
        // Distribute evenly
        return id.hashCode();  // Uses string's hashCode
    }

    @Override
    public boolean equals(Object o) {
        return ((GoodHash)o).id.equals(this.id);
    }
}
```

Proper equals() and hashCode() implementation prevent collision issues.

Three ordered/unordered map implementations with different characteristics.

## HashMap

```java
HashMap<String, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();
map.put("c", 3);
map.put("a", 1);
map.put("b", 2);

for (String key : map.keySet()) {
    System.out.println(key);
}
// Output: b, c, a (unpredictable order)
```

- **Order**: No order guaranteed
- **Performance**: O(1) average
- **Use Case**: When order doesn't matter

## LinkedHashMap

```java
LinkedHashMap<String, Integer> map = new LinkedHashMap<>();
map.put("c", 3);
map.put("a", 1);
map.put("b", 2);

for (String key : map.keySet()) {
    System.out.println(key);
}
// Output: c, a, b (insertion order)
```

- **Order**: Insertion order maintained
- **Performance**: O(1) average (doubly-linked list overhead)
- **Use Case**: When insertion order matters, LRU cache

```java
// LRU Cache with LinkedHashMap
class LRUCache<K, V> extends LinkedHashMap<K, V> {
    private int capacity;

    public LRUCache(int capacity) {
        super(capacity, 0.75f, true);  // true = access-order
        this.capacity = capacity;
    }

    @Override
    protected boolean removeEldestEntry(Map.Entry eldest) {
        return size() > capacity;  // Remove oldest on overflow
    }
}
```

## TreeMap

```java
TreeMap<String, Integer> map = new TreeMap<>();
map.put("c", 3);
map.put("a", 1);
map.put("b", 2);

for (String key : map.keySet()) {
    System.out.println(key);
}
// Output: a, b, c (sorted order)
```

- **Order**: Sorted by key
- **Performance**: O(log n) for get/put
- **Use Case**: When sorted order needed, range queries

```java
// Range queries
map.subMap("a", "c");      // Keys from "a" to "c" (excluding "c")
map.headMap("b");          // Keys before "b"
map.tailMap("b");          // Keys from "b" onward
map.ceilingKey("a1");      // First key >= "a1"
map.floorKey("b1");        // First key <= "b1"
```

## Comparison:

```
HashMap: Fastest (O(1)), no order
LinkedHashMap: Medium (O(1)), insertion order
TreeMap: Slower (O(log n)), sorted order
```

Choose based on requirements: speed vs ordering.

ConcurrentHashMap is a thread-safe Map using bucket-level locking instead of full synchronization.

## Segmentation Strategy

HashMap: One lock for entire map -> bottleneck
ConcurrentHashMap: Multiple locks (buckets/segments) -> better concurrency

```java
// Conceptual structure
private Segment<K,V>[] segments;  // Default 16 segments

// Each segment is independently locked
segments[0] -> locked separately
segments[1] -> locked separately
segments[2] -> locked separately

// Multiple threads can update different segments simultaneously
Thread1 updates segment[0] (locked)
Thread2 updates segment[1] (locked)  // No contention!
Thread3 updates segment[2] (locked)
```

## Put Operation

```java
ConcurrentHashMap<String, Integer> map = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();

// Thread 1
map.put("alice", 25);

// Thread 2
map.put("bob", 23);

// Steps:
// 1. Compute hash for key
// 2. Find segment (segment = hash % segmentCount)
// 3. Lock that segment only
// 4. Insert into bucket within segment
// 5. Unlock segment
```

## Get Operation

```java
// Get doesn't lock (or uses lock-free techniques in Java 8+)
Integer age = map.get("alice");

// Java 8+: Uses CAS (Compare-And-Swap) instead of locks
// Even faster than HashMap in many cases
```

## Concurrency Benefits

```java
HashMap<String, Integer> hashMap = new HashMap<>();
// Thread 1: hashMap.put("a", 1);  // Thread-safe code needed
// Thread 2: hashMap.put("b", 2);  // Both need synchronization

// With synchronization needed:
synchronized(hashMap) {
    hashMap.put("a", 1);  // One thread at a time
}

// ConcurrentHashMap: Built-in concurrency
ConcurrentHashMap<String, Integer> concMap = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();
concMap.put("a", 1);  // Thread 1: locks segment[hash("a")]
concMap.put("b", 2);  // Thread 2: locks segment[hash("b")] in parallel
```

## Real Production Example

```java
public class UserCache {
    private ConcurrentHashMap<Integer, User> cache = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();

    public void cacheUser(Integer id, User user) {
        cache.put(id, user);  // Thread-safe, segment-level locking
    }

    public User getUser(Integer id) {
        return cache.get(id);  // Lock-free in Java 8+
    }

    public int getCacheSize() {
        return cache.size();  // Atomic operation
    }
}
```

## Key Differences from Synchronized Collections

```
Synchronized Collections: synchronized(map) { operations }
ConcurrentHashMap: Built-in segment-level concurrency

Performance: ConcurrentHashMap much better under high contention
```

ConcurrentHashMap is the preferred choice for multi-threaded applications.

ArrayList and LinkedList are two implementations of List interface with different data structures.

## ArrayList: Array-Based

```java
ArrayList<String> list = new ArrayList<>();
list.add("alice");    // O(1) amortized
list.add("bob");      // O(1) amortized
list.add(1, "charlie");  // O(n) - shift elements

// Internal: dynamic array
// ┌────────────────────────────────┐
// │ [0]     [1]     [2]     [3]    │
// │ alice   bob   charlie  null    │
// └────────────────────────────────┘
```

## LinkedList: Linked Nodes

```java
LinkedList<String> list = new LinkedList<>();
list.add("alice");    // O(1)
list.add("bob");      // O(1)
list.add(1, "charlie");  // O(n) - walk to node

// Internal: doubly-linked nodes
// null <- [alice] <-> [bob] <-> [charlie] -> null
```

## Comparison:

```
Operation        ArrayList    LinkedList
-----------      ---------    ----------
add() end        O(1)         O(1)
add() middle     O(n)         O(n)
remove() middle  O(n)         O(n)
get(index)       O(1)         O(n)
Memory           Compact      Extra pointers
```

## Code Examples:

```java
// ArrayList: Fast random access
for (int i = 0; i < list.size(); i++) {
    String s = list.get(i);  // O(1)
}

// LinkedList: Fast insertion/deletion at ends
LinkedList<String> queue = new LinkedList<>();
queue.addFirst("data");   // O(1) - deque operations
queue.removeFirst();      // O(1)
```

## Real-World Impact:

```java
// Good: ArrayList for random access
List<User> users = new ArrayList<>();
User user = users.get(500);  // Fast, O(1)

// Bad: LinkedList for iteration
LinkedList<User> users = new LinkedList<>();
for (User u : users) {   // Iterates nodes, O(n)
    process(u);
}

// Good: LinkedList as queue
LinkedList<Task> queue = new LinkedList<>();
queue.addLast(task);     // O(1)
Task t = queue.removeFirst();  // O(1)
```

Use ArrayList by default unless you need specific LinkedList behaviors.

HashSet uses HashMap internally with keys as elements and dummy values, ensuring uniqueness through equals() and hashCode().

## Internal Structure

```java
public class HashSet<E> {
    private transient HashMap<E, Object> map;
    private static final Object PRESENT = new Object();

    public boolean add(E e) {
        return map.put(e, PRESENT) == null;
    }

    public boolean contains(Object o) {
        return map.containsKey(o);
    }
}
```

## Uniqueness Mechanism

```java
HashSet<String> set = new HashSet<>();
set.add("alice");   // Put in map with "alice" as key
set.add("bob");     // Put in map with "bob" as key
set.add("alice");   // "alice" already exists

// Result: only unique strings stored
for (String s : set) {
    System.out.println(s);  // alice, bob (no duplicates)
}
```

## Requires Proper equals() and hashCode()

```java
class User {
    String id;

    @Override
    public int hashCode() {
        return id.hashCode();
    }

    @Override
    public boolean equals(Object o) {
        User other = (User) o;
        return this.id.equals(other.id);
    }
}

HashSet<User> users = new HashSet<>();
users.add(new User("1"));
users.add(new User("1"));  // Duplicate detected via equals()
// Result: Set contains only 1 User
```

## Common Mistake: Broken equals/hashCode

```java
class BadUser {
    String id;

    // Only hashCode, no equals override
    @Override
    public int hashCode() {
        return id.hashCode();
    }
}

HashSet<BadUser> users = new HashSet<>();
users.add(new BadUser("1"));
users.add(new BadUser("1"));  // Treated as different objects
// Result: Set contains 2 items (duplicates not detected!)
```

HashSet ensures uniqueness by leveraging HashMap's key uniqueness.

Threads and processes are different units of execution with different isolation levels.

## Process

- Independent execution unit with own memory space
- Cannot directly access other process memory
- Creating process is expensive (separate JVM)
- Inter-process communication (IPC) needed

```java
// Separate processes (two JVMs)
// Process 1: java MyApp
// Process 2: java MyApp
// Memory isolated between them
```

## Thread

- Lightweight execution unit within same process
- Shares memory with other threads
- Creating thread is cheap
- Direct memory access between threads

```java
public class ThreadExample {
    static int counter = 0;  // Shared memory

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Thread t1 = new Thread(() -> {
            counter++;  // Thread 1 updates
        });

        Thread t2 = new Thread(() -> {
            counter++;  // Thread 2 updates, sees same counter
        });

        t1.start();
        t2.start();
        // Both threads update same counter
    }
}
```

## Comparison:

```
Process: Heavy, isolated, slow creation
Thread: Light, shared memory, fast creation

Process: Safe isolation
Thread: Requires synchronization for thread safety
```

## Real Example:

```java
// Threads in same process - shared static variable
class SharedData {
    static int data = 0;  // All threads see this
}

// Threads accessing shared data
Thread t1 = new Thread(() -> SharedData.data = 5);
Thread t2 = new Thread(() -> System.out.println(SharedData.data));

t1.start();
t2.start();
// t2 might print 5 (if t1 finishes first)
```

Threads are more efficient but require careful synchronization.

The synchronized keyword ensures that only one thread can execute a block of code at a time, using intrinsic locks.

## Synchronized Method

```java
public class Counter {
    private int count = 0;

    public synchronized void increment() {
        count++;  // Only one thread executes at a time
    }

    public synchronized int getCount() {
        return count;
    }
}

// Equivalent to locking "this" object
```

## Synchronized Block

```java
public class AdvancedCounter {
    private int count = 0;

    public void increment() {
        // Other code (non-synchronized)

        synchronized(this) {
            count++;  // Only this block synchronized
        }

        // Other code (non-synchronized)
    }
}
```

## How It Works

```
Thread 1: Tries to enter synchronized block
          │
          └─> Acquires lock on object
              Executes critical section
              Releases lock

Thread 2: Waits for lock
          │
          └─> Lock released by Thread 1
              Acquires lock
              Executes critical section
```

## Real Example

```java
public class BankAccount {
    private double balance = 1000;

    public synchronized void withdraw(double amount) {
        if (balance >= amount) {
            balance -= amount;  // Thread-safe
        }
    }

    public synchronized void deposit(double amount) {
        balance += amount;  // Thread-safe
    }
}

// Two threads can't execute withdraw/deposit simultaneously
Thread t1 = new Thread(() -> account.withdraw(100));
Thread t2 = new Thread(() -> account.deposit(50));
t1.start();
t2.start();
// Only one executes at a time
```

## Performance Cost

```java
// synchronized blocks can become bottlenecks
public synchronized void expensiveOperation() {
    // Lock held entire time
    database.query();    // Slow, lock still held
    processData();       // Slow, lock still held
    updateCache();       // Slow, lock still held
}

// Better: minimize lock scope
public void optimizedOperation() {
    List<Data> data;
    synchronized(this) {
        data = database.query();  // Quick lock
    }
    processData(data);     // No lock, parallel execution possible
    updateCache(data);     // No lock
}
```

synchronized is simple but can impact performance under contention.

The volatile keyword ensures visibility of variable changes across threads without synchronization, but doesn't guarantee atomicity.

## What volatile Does

```java
public class FlagExample {
    private volatile boolean flag = false;

    public void writer() {
        flag = true;  // Visible to all threads immediately
    }

    public void reader() {
        if (flag) {   // Always sees the latest value
            System.out.println("Flag is true");
        }
    }
}

// Without volatile: reader might see stale value (cached in CPU)
// With volatile: memory barrier ensures fresh read
```

## Memory Barrier Effect

```
Without volatile:
Thread 1: flag = true (CPU cache updated, not memory)
Thread 2: if (flag) (reads from CPU cache, sees old value!)

With volatile:
Thread 1: flag = true (CPU cache + memory synced via barrier)
Thread 2: if (flag) (memory barrier ensures fresh read)
```

## When to Use volatile

### 1. Simple Flags

```java
public class ShutdownManager {
    private volatile boolean shutdown = false;

    public void requestShutdown() {
        shutdown = true;  // Signal to stop
    }

    public void run() {
        while (!shutdown) {  // Responsive to shutdown signal
            processWork();
        }
    }
}
```

### 2. Status Updates

```java
public class ProgressTracker {
    private volatile int progress = 0;

    public void doWork() {
        for (int i = 0; i < 100; i++) {
            progress = i;  // Other threads see progress
        }
    }

    public int getProgress() {
        return progress;  // Always current value
    }
}
```

## What volatile DOESN'T Do

```java
private volatile int counter = 0;

// NOT thread-safe: counter++ is not atomic
public void increment() {
    counter++;  // Read, modify, write - not atomic!
}

// Thread 1: Read counter (5)
// Thread 2: Read counter (5)
// Thread 1: Increment to 6, write
// Thread 2: Increment to 6, write
// Result: counter = 6 (lost one increment!)

// Solution: Use synchronized or AtomicInteger
public synchronized void increment() {
    counter++;  // Atomic operation
}

private AtomicInteger atomicCounter = new AtomicInteger(0);
public void increment() {
    atomicCounter.incrementAndGet();  // Atomic
}
```

## Comparison

```
volatile: Visibility only, no atomicity, lightweight
synchronized: Visibility + atomicity, heavier weight
AtomicInteger: Visibility + atomicity, lock-free
```

volatile is ideal for simple visibility needs without atomicity.

Compare-And-Swap (CAS) is a lock-free atomic operation: compare a value and swap if equal, all atomically.

## How CAS Works

```
CAS(address, expectedValue, newValue):
  if (memory[address] == expectedValue) {
    memory[address] = newValue;
    return true;  // Success
  } else {
    return false; // Failure - value changed
  }
```

## AtomicInteger Example

```java
import java.util.concurrent.atomic.AtomicInteger;

AtomicInteger counter = new AtomicInteger(0);

// Traditional: synchronized
synchronized {
    int current = counter.get();
    counter.set(current + 1);  // Two operations
}

// CAS-based: lock-free
counter.incrementAndGet();  // Atomic single operation
```

## How AtomicInteger Uses CAS

```java
public class AtomicInteger {
    private volatile int value;

    public final boolean compareAndSet(int expect, int update) {
        // CAS operation (hardware-supported)
        return unsafe.compareAndSwapInt(this, valueOffset, expect, update);
    }

    public final int incrementAndGet() {
        int current, next;
        do {
            current = get();
            next = current + 1;
        } while (!compareAndSet(current, next));  // Retry if failed
        return next;
    }
}
```

## Real Usage

```java
public class CounterWithCAS {
    private AtomicInteger count = new AtomicInteger(0);

    public void increment() {
        count.incrementAndGet();  // Lock-free, CAS-based
    }

    public int getCount() {
        return count.get();
    }
}

// Faster than synchronized under high contention
// No blocking, just retry
```

## Comparison with Locks

```
Locks (synchronized):
- Thread blocks if lock held
- Context switch overhead
- Slower under high contention

CAS (AtomicInteger):
- Busy-wait retry loop
- No blocking
- Faster under high contention
- Can cause CPU spinning if many retries
```

CAS is the foundation of lock-free programming in Java.

ExecutorService and Thread are different approaches to multi-threaded execution.

## Thread: Direct Control

```java
Thread t1 = new Thread(() -> {
    System.out.println("Running in thread 1");
});
t1.start();  // Create and start single thread

// Issues:
// - Creating many threads is expensive
// - No thread reuse
// - Hard to manage many threads
```

## ExecutorService: Thread Pool

```java
ExecutorService executor = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(5);

for (int i = 0; i < 100; i++) {
    executor.execute(() -> {
        System.out.println("Task running");
    });
}

// Benefits:
// - Reuse 5 threads for 100 tasks
// - Automatic task queuing
// - Easy scalability
```

## Key Differences:

```
Thread: Manual thread creation, one task per thread
ExecutorService: Managed thread pool, multiple tasks per thread

Thread: No backpressure, can create unlimited threads
ExecutorService: Bounded queue, configurable rejection policy

Thread: Hard to shutdown gracefully
ExecutorService: Shutdown, shutdownNow, awaitTermination methods
```

## Real Production Code:

```java
ExecutorService executor = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(10);

try {
    for (Request req : requests) {
        executor.submit(() -> handleRequest(req));
    }
} finally {
    executor.shutdown();  // Orderly shutdown
    executor.awaitTermination(5, TimeUnit.SECONDS);
}
```

ExecutorService is preferred for scalable, manageable concurrent execution.

Deadlock occurs when two or more threads wait for resources held by each other, causing mutual blockage.

## Deadlock Example

```java
public class Deadlock {
    private Object lock1 = new Object();
    private Object lock2 = new Object();

    public void method1() {
        synchronized(lock1) {
            Thread.sleep(100);  // Hold lock1
            synchronized(lock2) {  // Wait for lock2
                System.out.println("Method 1");
            }
        }
    }

    public void method2() {
        synchronized(lock2) {  // Holds lock2
            Thread.sleep(100);
            synchronized(lock1) {  // Waits for lock1
                System.out.println("Method 2");
            }
        }
    }
}

// Thread 1: Acquires lock1, waits for lock2
// Thread 2: Acquires lock2, waits for lock1
// DEADLOCK!
```

## How to Avoid:

### 1. Lock Ordering
Acquire locks in consistent order.

```java
public void safeMethod1() {
    synchronized(lock1) {  // Always lock1 first
        synchronized(lock2) {
            // ...
        }
    }
}

public void safeMethod2() {
    synchronized(lock1) {  // Always lock1 first (same order)
        synchronized(lock2) {
            // ...
        }
    }
}
```

### 2. Timeout
Use timeout to escape potential deadlock.

```java
Lock lock1 = new ReentrantLock();
Lock lock2 = new ReentrantLock();

try {
    if (lock1.tryLock(1, TimeUnit.SECONDS) &&
        lock2.tryLock(1, TimeUnit.SECONDS)) {
        // Got both locks
    } else {
        // Timeout - avoid deadlock
    }
} catch (InterruptedException e) {
    // Handle
}
```

### 3. ReadWriteLock
Reduce lock contention.

```java
ReadWriteLock lock = new ReentrantReadWriteLock();

public void readData() {
    lock.readLock().lock();  // Multiple readers allowed
    try {
        // Read operation
    } finally {
        lock.readLock().unlock();
    }
}
```

## Prevention Principles:

```
1. Minimize locks
2. Acquire in same order
3. Use timeout
4. Avoid nested locks
5. Use higher-level concurrency utilities
```

Deadlock prevention requires careful design of lock acquisition patterns.

ThreadLocal provides thread-isolated storage, each thread gets its own independent copy of a variable.

## Basic Usage

```java
ThreadLocal<String> threadLocal = new ThreadLocal<>();

Thread t1 = new Thread(() -> {
    threadLocal.set("Value 1");
    System.out.println(threadLocal.get());  // Value 1
});

Thread t2 = new Thread(() -> {
    threadLocal.set("Value 2");
    System.out.println(threadLocal.get());  // Value 2
});

t1.start();
t2.start();
// Each thread sees its own value
```

## Use Cases:

### 1. Request Context (Web Applications)

```java
public class RequestContext {
    private static ThreadLocal<User> currentUser = new ThreadLocal<>();

    public static void setUser(User user) {
        currentUser.set(user);
    }

    public static User getUser() {
        return currentUser.get();
    }

    public static void clear() {
        currentUser.remove();  // IMPORTANT
    }
}

// In servlet
public void service() {
    User user = authenticateUser();
    RequestContext.setUser(user);
    try {
        handleRequest();  // Can access user without passing
    } finally {
        RequestContext.clear();
    }
}
```

### 2. Connection Per Thread

```java
public class DatabaseConnection {
    private static ThreadLocal<Connection> connThreadLocal =
        new ThreadLocal<>();

    public static Connection getConnection() {
        Connection conn = connThreadLocal.get();
        if (conn == null) {
            conn = createConnection();
            connThreadLocal.set(conn);
        }
        return conn;
    }
}
```

## Critical Issue: Memory Leak in Thread Pools

```java
// DANGEROUS with thread pools!
private static ThreadLocal<Data> cache = new ThreadLocal<>();

public void processRequest() {
    Data data = new Data();  // Large object
    cache.set(data);
    // ...
    // Forget to remove!
}

// Thread pool reuses threads
// ThreadLocal data persists across requests!
// Memory leak: Large objects accumulate
```

## Safe Usage in Thread Pools

```java
try {
    Data data = new Data();
    cache.set(data);
    processRequest();
} finally {
    cache.remove();  // ALWAYS remove in thread pools
}
```

## Common Pitfalls:

```
1. Forgetting to remove() in thread pools
2. Large objects held longer than needed
3. Memory leaks in long-running applications
4. Parent thread data visible to child threads
```

ThreadLocal is powerful but requires careful cleanup in managed environments.

Java exceptions fall into two categories: checked (must be caught) and unchecked (optional).

## Checked Exceptions

Must be caught or declared in method signature.

```java
public void readFile(String filename) throws IOException {
    FileReader reader = new FileReader(filename);  // Throws IOException
    // ...
}

// Caller must handle
try {
    readFile("data.txt");
} catch (IOException e) {
    e.printStackTrace();
}
```

## Unchecked Exceptions

Don't require explicit handling (though good practice to catch).

```java
public void divideNumbers(int a, int b) {
    int result = a / b;  // Can throw ArithmeticException
    System.out.println(result);
}

// Caller doesn't need to catch
divideNumbers(10, 0);  // ArithmeticException may throw
```

## Comparison:

```
Checked: IOException, SQLException, ParseException
Unchecked: NullPointerException, ArithmeticException, ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException

Checked: Compiler enforces handling
Unchecked: Compiler doesn't enforce

Checked: For recoverable errors
Unchecked: For programming errors
```

## Examples:

```java
// Checked - must handle
try {
    connection = DriverManager.getConnection(url);
} catch (SQLException e) {
    logger.error("Database connection failed", e);
}

// Unchecked - optional
try {
    int index = list.get(100);  // IndexOutOfBoundsException
} catch (IndexOutOfBoundsException e) {
    // Handle if needed
}
```

Understanding checked vs unchecked ensures proper error handling.

If an exception isn't caught, it propagates up the call stack until caught or the program terminates.

## Propagation Example

```java
public class ExceptionPropagation {
    public void level3() {
        int x = 1 / 0;  // ArithmeticException thrown
    }

    public void level2() {
        level3();  // Exception propagates up
    }

    public void level1() {
        level2();  // Exception propagates up
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new ExceptionPropagation().level1();  // Unhandled!
    }
}

// Output:
// Exception in thread "main" java.lang.ArithmeticException: / by zero
// at ExceptionPropagation.level3(ExceptionPropagation.java:5)
// at ExceptionPropagation.level2(ExceptionPropagation.java:9)
// at ExceptionPropagation.level1(ExceptionPropagation.java:13)
// at ExceptionPropagation.main(ExceptionPropagation.java:17)
// [Program terminates]
```

## With Proper Handling

```java
try {
    level1();
} catch (ArithmeticException e) {
    logger.error("Calculation error", e);
    // Program continues
}
```

## Real Production Impact

```java
// Unhandled exception in thread terminates thread
ExecutorService executor = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(5);

executor.execute(() -> {
    int x = 1 / 0;  // Unhandled exception
    // Thread dies silently, task incomplete
});

// Better: handle in task
executor.execute(() -> {
    try {
        int x = 1 / 0;
    } catch (ArithmeticException e) {
        logger.error("Task failed", e);
    }
});
```

Unhandled exceptions cause abrupt program termination or thread death.

The finally block executes regardless of exception occurrence, used for cleanup (closing resources).

## Finally Always Executes

```java
try {
    // Code that may throw exception
    int x = 1 / 0;
    System.out.println("After division");  // Not executed
} catch (ArithmeticException e) {
    System.out.println("Caught exception");
} finally {
    System.out.println("Finally block");  // ALWAYS executes
}

// Output:
// Caught exception
// Finally block
```

## Exception Not Caught

```java
try {
    FileInputStream fis = new FileInputStream("file.txt");
} finally {
    fis.close();  // Executes even if exception not caught
}
// Exception still propagates after finally
```

## When It's Skipped

```java
// 1. System.exit() called
try {
    System.exit(0);
} finally {
    System.out.println("Never prints");  // Skipped
}

// 2. Infinite loop in try block
try {
    while (true) {  // Never returns
        System.out.println("Infinite loop");
    }
} finally {
    System.out.println("Never prints");  // Never reaches
}

// 3. JVM crash or hard kill
```

## Real Usage: Resource Management

```java
// Old way (error-prone)
Connection conn = null;
try {
    conn = getConnection();
    executeQuery(conn);
} catch (SQLException e) {
    logger.error("Query failed", e);
} finally {
    if (conn != null) {
        try {
            conn.close();  // Cleanup
        } catch (SQLException e) {
            logger.error("Close failed", e);
        }
    }
}

// Modern way (try-with-resources)
try (Connection conn = getConnection()) {
    executeQuery(conn);  // Auto-closed in finally
} catch (SQLException e) {
    logger.error("Query failed", e);
}
```

finally is essential for guaranteed cleanup operations.

equals() and hashCode() must be consistent: objects that are equal must have the same hashCode.

## The Contract

```
If a.equals(b) == true, then a.hashCode() == b.hashCode()
```

## Why Together?

If you break this contract, hash-based collections (HashMap, HashSet) fail:

```java
class User {
    String id;
    String name;

    @Override
    public boolean equals(Object o) {
        User other = (User) o;
        return this.id.equals(other.id);  // Only compare ID
    }

    // WRONG: Only hashes name
    @Override
    public int hashCode() {
        return name.hashCode();  // Different from equals!
    }
}

// Problem:
User user1 = new User("1", "Alice");
User user2 = new User("1", "Bob");   // Same ID, different name

user1.equals(user2);  // true (same ID)
user1.hashCode() == user2.hashCode();  // false (different name)

// In HashSet:
HashSet<User> set = new HashSet<>();
set.add(user1);
set.add(user2);
// Result: Set contains 2 items (should be 1!)
// They're equal but have different hashes -> treated as different
```

## Correct Implementation

```java
class User {
    String id;

    @Override
    public boolean equals(Object o) {
        User other = (User) o;
        return this.id.equals(other.id);
    }

    @Override
    public int hashCode() {
        return id.hashCode();  // Consistent with equals
    }
}

HashSet<User> set = new HashSet<>();
set.add(new User("1"));
set.add(new User("1"));  // Duplicate detected correctly
// Result: Set contains 1 item
```

## Real Production Impact

```java
// Bad: Collections malfunction
Map<BadUser, String> map = new HashMap<>();
BadUser user1 = new BadUser("1", "Alice");
BadUser user2 = new BadUser("1", "Bob");

map.put(user1, "Alice's value");
System.out.println(map.get(user2));  // null (should be "Alice's value")
// Because hashCode differs, lookup fails

// Good: Consistent implementation
Map<User, String> map = new HashMap<>();
User user1 = new User("1", "Alice");
User user2 = new User("1", "Bob");

map.put(user1, "Alice's value");
System.out.println(map.get(user2));  // "Alice's value" (correct)
```

equals() and hashCode() are intrinsically linked - override both or neither.

An immutable class cannot change its state after creation. Once constructed, its fields are final and don't change.

## Requirements for Immutability

```java
public final class ImmutableUser {
    // 1. All fields must be final
    private final String id;
    private final String name;
    private final int age;

    // 2. Constructor initializes all fields
    public ImmutableUser(String id, String name, int age) {
        this.id = id;
        this.name = name;
        this.age = age;
    }

    // 3. Only getters, no setters
    public String getId() { return id; }
    public String getName() { return name; }
    public int getAge() { return age; }

    // 4. If field is mutable, create defensive copy
    private final List<String> tags;

    public ImmutableUser(String id, List<String> tags) {
        this.tags = new ArrayList<>(tags);  // Defensive copy
    }

    public List<String> getTags() {
        return new ArrayList<>(tags);  // Return copy, not reference
    }
}
```

## Key Points:

```
1. final keyword on class - prevents subclassing
2. final keyword on fields - prevents reassignment
3. No setters - prevents field modification
4. Defensive copies - prevent external modification
5. Override hashCode/equals - safe for collections
```

## Example: String (Immutable)

```java
String str = "Hello";
str.substring(0, 3);  // Returns "Hel", doesn't modify original
str.toUpperCase();    // Returns "HELLO", str still "Hello"

String str2 = str;    // Safe to share reference
str2 = str.concat(" World");  // Creates new String, doesn't modify
```

## Real Benefits

```java
// Thread-safe without synchronization
ImmutableUser user = new ImmutableUser("1", "Alice", 25);

Thread t1 = new Thread(() -> {
    System.out.println(user.getName());  // Safe
});

Thread t2 = new Thread(() -> {
    System.out.println(user.getAge());  // Safe
});

// No synchronization needed!

// Safe as HashMap key
Map<ImmutableUser, String> map = new HashMap<>();
map.put(user, "value");
// User's hashCode never changes
```

Immutable classes are thread-safe by design and safe for caching.

Three string classes with different mutability and thread-safety characteristics.

## String: Immutable

```java
String str = "Hello";
str.concat(" World");  // Returns new String, original unchanged
String newStr = str + " World";  // Creates new String

// Immutable - thread-safe but inefficient in loops
```

## StringBuilder: Mutable, Not Thread-Safe

```java
StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder("Hello");
sb.append(" World");  // Modifies in place
sb.insert(0, "Say ");  // More efficient

String result = sb.toString();
```

## StringBuffer: Mutable, Thread-Safe

```java
StringBuffer sb = new StringBuffer("Hello");
sb.append(" World");  // Synchronized, thread-safe

String result = sb.toString();
```

## Comparison:

```
String: Immutable, thread-safe, slow in loops
StringBuilder: Mutable, fast, not thread-safe (single-threaded)
StringBuffer: Mutable, thread-safe, slower (synchronized)
```

## Real Performance:

```java
// WRONG: String concatenation in loop
String result = "";
for (int i = 0; i < 10000; i++) {
    result += "Item " + i;  // Creates new String each iteration!
    // Performance: O(n^2)
}

// CORRECT: Use StringBuilder
StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
for (int i = 0; i < 10000; i++) {
    sb.append("Item ").append(i);
}
String result = sb.toString();  // Single allocation
// Performance: O(n)
```

## When to Use:

```
String: String values that don't change
StringBuilder: String building in single thread (most common)
StringBuffer: String building with multiple threads (rare)
```

StringBuilder is almost always preferred over StringBuffer today.

Class loader is responsible for loading Java classes into memory during runtime.

## Class Loader Hierarchy

```
Bootstrap ClassLoader (JVM)
        │
        ├─ Load: rt.jar (core Java classes)
        ├─ Load: java.lang, java.util, etc.
        │
Extension ClassLoader
        │
        ├─ Load: lib/ext/*.jar files
        │
Application ClassLoader
        │
        └─ Load: Application classes from classpath
```

## How Class Loading Works

```java
public class ClassLoaderDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String className = "com.example.MyClass";

        // ClassLoader loads the class
        Class<?> clazz = Class.forName(className);
        // Steps:
        // 1. Check if already loaded (cache)
        // 2. If not, load from classpath
        // 3. Link (verify, prepare, resolve)
        // 4. Initialize (static blocks)
    }
}
```

## Real Example

```java
public class User {
    static {
        System.out.println("User class initialized");  // When loaded
    }

    public User() {
        System.out.println("User instance created");   // When instantiated
    }
}

// First load:
Class<?> clazz = Class.forName("User");  // Prints "User class initialized"

// Second load:
User user = new User();  // Prints "User instance created" (class already loaded)
```

## Custom ClassLoader

```java
public class CustomClassLoader extends ClassLoader {
    @Override
    public Class<?> findClass(String name) throws ClassNotFoundException {
        // Load class from custom location
        byte[] classData = loadClassData(name);
        return defineClass(name, classData, 0, classData.length);
    }

    private byte[] loadClassData(String name) {
        // Load from network, database, etc.
        return new byte[0];
    }
}
```

## Parent Delegation

```
Application wants: String
        │
        └─> Application ClassLoader
                │ Ask parent?
                └─> Extension ClassLoader
                        │ Ask parent?
                        └─> Bootstrap ClassLoader
                                │ Found!
                                └─> Return String class
```

## Real Production Impact

```java
// Memory leak: Unreleased ClassLoader holds classes
ClassLoader customLoader = new URLClassLoader(...);
Class<?> clazz = customLoader.loadClass("MyClass");
// If customLoader not cleaned up, classes stay in memory

// Proper cleanup:
try {
    // Use custom loader
} finally {
    ((URLClassLoader) customLoader).close();  // Release resources
}
```

Class loaders enable dynamic loading and plugin architectures.

A functional interface is an interface with exactly one abstract method, enabling lambda expression support.

## Definition

```java
@FunctionalInterface
public interface Calculator {
    int calculate(int a, int b);  // Single abstract method
}

// Can implement with lambda
Calculator add = (a, b) -> a + b;
System.out.println(add.calculate(5, 3));  // 8

// Equivalent to anonymous class
Calculator add = new Calculator() {
    @Override
    public int calculate(int a, int b) {
        return a + b;
    }
};
```

## Common Functional Interfaces

```java
// Predicate: test condition
Predicate<Integer> isPositive = n -> n > 0;
isPositive.test(5);  // true

// Function: transform input to output
Function<String, Integer> toLength = s -> s.length();
toLength.apply("Hello");  // 5

// Consumer: accept input, no return
Consumer<String> print = s -> System.out.println(s);
print.accept("Hello");  // Prints Hello

// Supplier: provide value
Supplier<String> hello = () -> "Hello";
hello.get();  // Returns "Hello"
```

## With Streams

```java
List<Integer> numbers = Arrays.asList(1, 2, 3, 4, 5);

// Predicate: filter
numbers.stream()
    .filter(n -> n > 2)
    .forEach(System.out::println);  // 3, 4, 5

// Function: map
numbers.stream()
    .map(n -> n * 2)
    .forEach(System.out::println);  // 2, 4, 6, 8, 10
```

## Custom Functional Interface

```java
@FunctionalInterface
public interface Formatter {
    String format(String input);  // Single method

    default String formatWithPrefix(String input) {
        return "[PREFIX] " + format(input);
    }
}

Formatter uppercase = s -> s.toUpperCase();
System.out.println(uppercase.format("hello"));  // HELLO

// Can have default methods without affecting @FunctionalInterface
```

## Why Important

```
1. Enable lambda expressions
2. Simplify code for simple operations
3. Enable functional programming style
4. Work with Stream API
```

Functional interfaces are the gateway to functional programming in Java.
